7:["$","article",null,{"className":" pb-16","children":[["$","$L1a",null,{}],"$L1b",["$","div",null,{"className":"relative flex items-end","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"container z-10 relative lg:grid lg:grid-cols-[1fr_48rem_1fr] text-white pb-8","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"col-start-1 col-span-1 md:col-start-2 md:col-span-2","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"uppercase text-sm mb-6","children":[["$","$3","0",{"children":["Writing Process",",  "]}],["$","$3","1",{"children":["Behind the Scenes",",  "]}],["$","$3","2",{"children":["Novel Updates",",  "]}],["$","$3","3",{"children":["Resources",false]}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"","children":["$","h1",null,{"className":"mb-6 text-3xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl","children":"What's a Pantser? Where do I begin?"}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"flex flex-col md:flex-row gap-4 md:gap-16","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex flex-col gap-4","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"flex flex-col gap-1","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm","children":"Author"}],[["$","$3","0",{"children":["Mandy",false,false,false]}]]]}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"flex flex-col gap-1","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm","children":"Date Published"}],["$","time",null,{"dateTime":"2025-03-30T18:15:00.000Z","children":"03/30/2025"}]]}]]}]]}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"min-h-[80vh] select-none","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"$undefined","children":["$","$L1c",null,{"fill":true,"imgClassName":"-z-10 object-cover","resource":{"id":25,"alt":"A blue door set into a wall of old fashioned and vintage books","caption":null,"updatedAt":"2025-02-20T17:40:36.730Z","createdAt":"2025-02-20T17:40:36.730Z","url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/book wall.jpg","thumbnailURL":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/book wall-300x190.jpg","filename":"book wall.jpg","mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":89489,"width":640,"height":406,"focalX":50,"focalY":50,"sizes":{"thumbnail":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/book wall-300x190.jpg","width":300,"height":190,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":23688,"filename":"book wall-300x190.jpg"},"square":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/book wall-500x500.jpg","width":500,"height":500,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":72329,"filename":"book wall-500x500.jpg"},"small":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/book wall-600x381.jpg","width":600,"height":381,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":78147,"filename":"book wall-600x381.jpg"},"medium":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/book wall-900x571.jpg","width":900,"height":571,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":138984,"filename":"book wall-900x571.jpg"},"large":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/book wall-1400x888.jpg","width":1400,"height":888,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":251805,"filename":"book wall-1400x888.jpg"},"xlarge":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/book wall-1920x1218.jpg","width":1920,"height":1218,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":380113,"filename":"book wall-1920x1218.jpg"}}}}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"absolute pointer-events-none left-0 bottom-0 w-full h-1/2 bg-gradient-to-t from-black to-transparent"}]]}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"flex flex-col items-center gap-4 pt-8","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"container","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"prose dark:prose-invert max-w-[48rem] mx-auto","children":[["$","p","0",{"className":"col-start-2","children":[["$","$3","0",{"children":"Today I decided to write a little bit about how I begin writing a new story. Every author is different, so take what I say with a grain of salt. If what I suggest doesn’t work for you, find your own path and you do you! This is absolutely not a one-size-fits-all deal. Every book (even within the same genres!) are all different because the authors are all different."}]]}],["$","p","1",{"className":"col-start-2","children":[["$","$3","0",{"children":"Now, into the good stuff."}]]}],["$","p","2",{"className":"col-start-2","children":[["$","$3","0",{"children":"I used to be a “pantser” (aka, someone who just sits down and starts writing by the seat of their pants.) This kind of author doesn’t know what’ll happen next. They don’t have any plans for the future, they let the characters tell their story. It’s an incredibly exciting and rewarding way to write stories and bravo to those authors! I loved writing like this because it made me feel adventurous and like I was on the ride, alongside my characters. (My Rose Winters novellas were both pantsed novels. Stephen King also reportedly pantses his stories.)"}]]}],["$","p","3",{"className":"col-start-2","children":[["$","$3","0",{"children":"Nothing short of immense awe goes to those authors who are “planners” either. These are the authors who, well, plan their story. They have varying levels of detail for themselves. Some planning authors plan every little character arc, every plot detail, everything short of the actual conversations. (though some do throw in ideas of what scenes could be, by including dialogue or scenery or what have you.) These are the authors you picture with the “idea wall” and sticky notes everywhere. JK Rowling and EL Stein both admit to being planners. (We can totally see the crazy detail oriented Planner JKR is by her entire Pottermore website having crazy amounts of detail you would never even think of. Like the bathroom announcement. Don’t ask.)"}]]}],["$","p","4",{"className":"col-start-2","children":[["$","$3","0",{"children":"With my last several projects I have become a mix of these two, a “plantser” if you will. I have the general idea of my story and what is supposed to happen. But I am still that person texting my best friend near tears and saying, “my character is doing something I don’t like!” and completely changing the rest of my outline from there. For the purpose of this post I’m going to talk about my Nanowrimo 2018 experience. I hadn’t “won” a Nano in 4 years. (When I say win I mean reaching 50,000 words in a novel in 30 days.) I was determined to win that year because I wanted the discount code to Scrivener, a program I use to this day."}]]}],["$","p","5",{"className":"col-start-2","children":[["$","$3","0",{"children":"For 2018 I started with the basics. I had an idea (I wanted to write a story about Merlin, King Arthur, and a secret.) I started by naming my characters. Merlin and Arthur were obvious. But I went to "}],["$","$L15","1",{"className":"","href":"https://www.behindthename.com/","rel":"noopener noreferrer","target":"_blank","children":["$undefined",[["$","$3","0",{"children":"my favorite naming website"}]]]}],["$","$3","2",{"children":" and started looking up other medieval names that I liked. I sent a list of them to some friends to narrow down and came to two different names. With those two names I had two different plots my story could take. I decided to merge the two, choose my favorite name, and go from there. I finished naming all of the characters I needed to. Then I went and found the "}],["$","$L15","3",{"className":"","href":"https://timstout.wordpress.com/story-structure/blake-snyders-beat-sheet/","rel":"noopener noreferrer","target":"_blank","children":["$undefined",[["$","$3","0",{"children":"Save the Cat Beat Sheet "}]]]}],["$","$3","4",{"children":"which I love dearly for planning. (This link leads you to explanations of each beat.)"}]]}],["$","p","6",{"className":"col-start-2","children":[["$","$3","0",{"children":"Once I got an idea of what each “beat” would mean, I sat back and looked at what I had created. I knew who my main characters were, what makes them tick, and even found pictures on Pinterest to represent who each of my characters would be. (Merlin was represented by a nice picture of Harrison Ford, my female main character’s mother played by Blake Lively.) I even had a friend model for me so I could make a temporary cover for my book for the competition."}]]}],["$","p","7",{"className":"col-start-2","children":[["$","$3","0",{"children":"Once I had all of that done, I still, regrettably, had about a month until Nanowrimo. But I felt like I wanted to get to know my characters a little bit more. I found a copy of 2018’s “inktober” prompts. These prompts are meant for artists, not writers. But it still worked. Each day of October you were given a single word as a prompt. Artists use this prompt in order to spread their talents and learn to do new art they wouldn’t normally do, or challenge themselves in their own medium and style. I took each of those words and every day would write a scene or a paragraph based on that word. Some days were super easy, others were a bit of a challenge. And one in particular (whale) I straight up had no idea how to incorporate. It was a fun way to learn who my characters were and how they acted. Only a few of those scenes ended up in my novel by the end of November. The rest of them were just fun to imagine side conversations."}]]}],["$","p","8",{"className":"col-start-2","children":[["$","$3","0",{"children":"By the time I sat down to write my story I had my cast of characters, my plot structure, and several scenes to help me get started. Despite this, my ending "}],["$","em","1",{"children":["$","$3","1",{"children":"did"}]}],["$","$3","2",{"children":" change by the time I was done with the first draft. (Characters still have control over their story in my process a wee bit.) I "}],["$","em","3",{"children":["$","$3","3",{"children":"did"}]}],["$","$3","4",{"children":" have a side character who surprised me. And that is where I get to enjoy the pantsing part of my story. I enjoy letting the characters take the wheel. Even if it throws me off and put me behind a few days in the competition. I "}],["$","em","5",{"children":["$","$3","5",{"children":"still made it"}]}],["$","$3","6",{"children":".  Now, 7 years later, my ending still looks worlds different and the editing process has sometimes felt overwhelming. But the fact is - I wrote a 50,000 word (about 140 pages in A5 size) first draft in 30 days."}]]}],["$","p","9",{"className":"col-start-2","children":[["$","$3","0",{"children":"That project was "}],["$","em","1",{"children":["$","$3","1",{"children":"Pulchra Arcanum"}]}],["$","$3","2",{"children":" and the first book of 3 will be (hopefully) releasing later this year. Subscribe to my newsletter and (or) follow me on social media for updates!"}]]}],["$","p","10",{"className":"col-start-2","children":[["$","$3","0",{"children":"As always, if there is a question I didn’t answer, let me know! I would love to answer it for you yourself, and then also add in an article talking about it."}]]}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"container mt-12 max-w-[52rem] lg:grid lg:grid-cols-subgrid col-start-1 col-span-3 grid-rows-[2fr]","children":["$undefined",["$","div",null,{"className":"grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 md:gap-8 items-stretch","children":[["$","$L1d","0",{"doc":{"id":4,"title":"Introductions","categories":[{"id":7,"title":"Behind the Scenes","parent":null,"breadcrumbs":[{"id":"67913df2d94eaa4a0d933d6d","doc":7,"url":null,"label":"Behind the Scenes"}],"updatedAt":"2025-01-22T18:50:26.922Z","createdAt":"2025-01-22T18:50:26.894Z"}],"meta":{"image":{"id":8,"alt":"The letters MT in a gold flowy font with intricate details in the background including a dragon and a pen with a dagger hilt.","caption":null,"updatedAt":"2025-01-23T18:31:04.710Z","createdAt":"2025-01-23T18:31:04.710Z","url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e.jpg","thumbnailURL":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-300x266.jpg","filename":"8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e.jpg","mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":49791,"width":667,"height":591,"focalX":50,"focalY":50,"sizes":{"thumbnail":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-300x266.jpg","width":300,"height":266,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":15266,"filename":"8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-300x266.jpg"},"square":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-500x500.jpg","width":500,"height":500,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":37265,"filename":"8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-500x500.jpg"},"small":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-600x532.jpg","width":600,"height":532,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":41142,"filename":"8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-600x532.jpg"},"medium":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-900x797.jpg","width":900,"height":797,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":69634,"filename":"8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-900x797.jpg"},"large":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-1400x1240.jpg","width":1400,"height":1240,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":126678,"filename":"8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-1400x1240.jpg"},"xlarge":{"url":"http://localhost:3000/api/media/file/8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-1920x1701.jpg","width":1920,"height":1701,"mimeType":"image/jpeg","filesize":194244,"filename":"8b2dd22d-9b86-45ee-8e27-d4fca428f57e-1920x1701.jpg"}}},"description":"I write for an audience. It's what motivates me. I want to have conversations with my readers!  I am so glad you're here."},"slug":"introductions"},"relationTo":"posts","showCategories":true}]]}]]}]]}]}]]}]
